What qualities make Novak Djokovic so dominant at tennis?¶

In the year 2021, Novak Djokovic has dominated the ATP tour, winning the first three grand slams to equal his career rivals, Rafael Nadal and Roger Federer at 20 grand slams each. In this document, we will examine attributes in Novak Djokovic's game by utilization of "The Data Science Pipeline". This pipeline is comprised of 5 stages: 1. Data Collection, 2. Data Management, 3. Exploratory Data Analysis, 4. Machine Learning, and 5. Communication of Insights Attained.

Section 1: Data Collection¶

The data below is extracted from 4 tsv files that were acquired from this website http://www.tennisabstract.com/cgi-bin/leaders.cgi?f=s00w1. The four datasets are read into a panda dataframe and then merged to create one main dataframe.

Section 2: Data Management¶

The data obtained from the TSV file is fairly tidy but there are some changes we have to make before we can effectively run analysis on the data. First, the percentage signs that occur in elements of some columns need to be removed, because otherwise these columns will not be able to be used. Second, these same elements from columns with percentage signs are currently string values and need to be changed to be float values. There is fortunately no missing data.

Section 3: Exploratory Data Analysis¶

In our dataframe, the column named M W% stands for match winning percentage. Since winning matches is the outcome that makes Novak Djokovic so successful, it can be viewed as our dependent variable. We are going to create a correlation matrix between the columns of the dataframe, and will examine specifically how the different columns correlate with match winning percentage. The correlation matrix is displayed using Seaborn, a useful statistical data visualization library, via the heatmap function.

In [18]:
plt.subplots(figsize = (35,25))
g = sns.heatmap(df.corr(), annot = True)

g.set_title("Correlation Matrix of Tennis Dataframe Columns")
Out[18]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Correlation Matrix of Tennis Dataframe Columns')

The heatmap above shows the correlation coefficients between all column variables in the tennis dataframe. This coefficient, named the r value, ranges from [-1,1] which 0 to 1 is measuring how strongly positively correlated the two variables are, and 0 to -1 is measuring how strongly negatively correlated the two variables are. Correlation coefficients between 0.0 and 0.3 have a weak or no correlation, between 0.3 and 0.5 have a weak-moderate correlation, between 0.5-0.7 have a moderate correlation, and between 0.7-1.0 have a strong correlation. We will examine variables than have a correlation greater than 0.5 with match winning percentage, M W%. These variables are listed below, along with their respective correlation coefficients with match winning percentage. Some variables that have a moderate or high correlation with match winning percentage were removed do to a duplicate nature. For instance Bks/S: Return Games Won per Set was used so Bks/M: Return Games Won per Match was removed.

M, Matches Played: 0.51

SPW, Percentage of Service Points Won: 0.67
2nd%, Second Serve Points Win Percentage: 0.70
Hld%, Hold Rate, Percentage of Service Games Won: 0.68
Pts/SG, Points Played per Service Game: -0.67
PtsL/SG, Points Lost per Service Game: -0.70
BPConv, Break Points Opportunities Converted: 0.64
BPChnc, Break Point Chances: 0.61
Bks/S: Return Games Won per Set: 0.5
BPSvd%: Percentage of Break Point Saved while Serving: 0.56
BPvs/G: Break Points Faced per Game: -0.63
Bkn/S: Service Games Lost per Set: -0.71

Section 4: Machine Learning¶

In this section we are going to use machine learning to find the linear regressions between match winning percentage and the various predictor variables it is moderately to highly correlated with, listed above. An import aspect of data science and the data science pipeline is understanding how to leverage helpful libraries in order to accomplish desired tasks. In this section we are going to use sklearn, a machine learning library, in order to find these linear regressions. The function used to create a linear regression model is sklearn's linear_model.LinearRegression() and that model can be fit with columns from the tennis dataframe to create the linear regression. It is highly recommended that the reader looks into documentation for sklearn if they are curious about its capabilities and other machine learning tasks that sklearn can accomplish. A critical aspect of data science is being comfortable with documentation and it is an extremely helpful resource! https://scikit-learn.org/stable/user_guide.html

Additionally we'll be using another data visualization library named matplotlib, in order to create scatter plots and their respective linear regressions for plots Match Winning percentage vs "Predictor Variable X" where variable X is the correlated variable.

We are hypothesizing that match win perccentage is correlated with each predictor variable. This creates a hypothesis and respective null hypothesis for match win percentage and each predictor variable, with the null hypothesis being that matching win percentage is not correlated with predictor variable X. The p value for each linear regression will help us decide if we can reject the null hypothesis.

In [4]:
winPerc = df['M W%'].to_numpy()
SPW = df['SPW'].to_numpy().reshape((-1,1))

lm = linear_model.LinearRegression()
lm.fit(SPW, winPerc)
fig3, ax3, = plt.subplots()

ax3.scatter(SPW, winPerc)
ax3.plot(SPW, lm.predict(SPW), color='red')
ax3.set(xlabel="Percentage of Service Points Won", ylabel="Match Win Percentage", title="Match Win Percentage vs. Percentage of Service Points Won")

novakDF = df[df['Player'] == "Novak Djokovic [SRB]"]
novakX = df['SPW'][0]
novakMWP = novakDF['M W%'][0]
plt.text(novakX, novakMWP, "Novak Djokovic")

rSquared = r2_score(winPerc, lm.predict(SPW))
slope, intercept, r_value, p_value, std_err = stats.linregress(df['SPW'].to_numpy(), winPerc)

print("The R squared value is: " +str(rSquared))
print("The p value is: " +str(p_value))

The R squared value is: 0.4521908466934156
The p value is: 8.882330089399635e-08

Exploratory Data Analysis Revisted¶


To further our analysis of this data we are going to step away from examining Djokovic and look at these predictor variables as a grouping to see if we can create a multiple linear regression in order to predict match win percentage. This takes us back to the Exploratory Data Anaylsis phase in the Data Science Pipeline. A key aspect of the pipeline is revisiting phases is order to gain new insights on the data. To this point we have created single linear regressions in regards to the correlations between match win percentage and a variety of other variables it is moderate to highly correlated with. These other variables have been treated as independent variables, and we are going to try to see if they are truly independent, which would allow for us to use multiple linear regression to represent match win percentage and the variable it depends on. We will plot another correlation matrix through a seaborn heatmap, this time using the reduced column variables. This will have the same information as the correlation matrix in section 3, but will be more readable and easier to compare all variables in the matrix instead of focusing on a single column. In order to accomplish this, a subset of the tennis dataframe will be created.

Out[17]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Correlation Matrix of Tennis Subset Dataframe Columns')

When looking at this correlation matrix, it is evident that many of these predictor variables are highly correlated with one another. This makes sense because all of these variables are various aspects of a player's serve and return game, so variables that involve a player's serve are highly correlated as are variables that involve a player's return. This is called multicollinearity and in multiple regression analysis it is important for multicollinearity to not occur, meaning that we only want to include predictors that are not correlated. In our scenario this makes the creation of a multiple linear regression more complicated because of the question of which predictor variables to include. If we include all of these predictor variables, then due to multicollinearity we would have a high standard of error on the coefficients for the multiple linear regression equation.

Section 5: Communication of Insights Attained¶

Through visualization of match win percentage against different predictor variables in the form of a scattor plot and linear regression lines we can see that for the 2021 tennis season, Novak Djokovic is performing above average in all aspects of his game. Both in service game and return game, Djokovic is playing at an elite level. During this analysis, we also showed the correlation between match win percentage and different predictor variables.
Tennis has many "games" within the game, and so it is interesting to see which predictor variables had a higher correlation with winning percentage. Here again is the list of predictor variables that were correlated with match win percentage:

M, Matches Played: 0.51

SPW, Percentage of Service Points Won: 0.67
2nd%, Second Serve Points Win Percentage: 0.70
Hld%, Hold Rate, Percentage of Service Games Won: 0.68
Pts/SG, Points Played per Service Game: -0.67
PtsL/SG, Points Lost per Service Game: -0.70
BPConv, Break Points Opportunities Converted: 0.64
BPChnc, Break Point Chances: 0.61
Bks/S: Return Games Won per Set: 0.5
BPSvd%: Percentage of Break Point Saved while Serving: 0.56
BPvs/G: Break Points Faced per Game: -0.63
Bkn/S: Service Games Lost per Set: -0.71

When thinking about each of these predictor variables, it makes logical sense that they are correlated with match win percentage. For instance, it makes sense that winning a higher percentage of service points, SPW, positively correlates with winning more matches. SPW and matching winning percentage had a correlation of 0.67. The interesting point here is insights gained from comparing column variables that were not including in this subset to the ones that were. For instance percentage of return points won, RPW, had a weak-moderate correlation of 0.44. Intuitvely, we might have thought since winning a high percentage of service points had moderate to almost high correlation with match winning percentage, that winning a high perccentage of return points would also have that high correlation with match winning percentage. In tennis, people tend to "hold their serve" or win games in which they are serving, so it is understandable that match win percentage has a higher correlation with percentage of service points won. This also means that people tend to win return games not as frequently, which is shown in the moderately weaker correlation between percentage of service points won and match winning percentage. But here is the interesting insight! When a player is able to string together wins on return points and gain a break point opportunity, it is important for them to capitalize. This is shown by the higher moderate correlation between predictor variable break point opportunities converted and match win percentage of 0.64. This shows a high stress, high importance moments in tennis and is one where, as we saw in the plots, Novak Djokovic excells. Another one, on serve, is second serve points win percent which had a 0.70 correlation with match win percentage. A second serve is usually at a much slower pace than a first serve, in order to avoid a double fault, and therefore gives an opponent a greater opporunitiy to win a point againt your serve. This analysis valids insight that this is an important point in tennis, as shows that again Novak Djokovic performs above average in this situation.

The data obtained unforunately only included the 2021 tennis season. If more data was avaliable, we could perform the same analysis for multiple years, as well as a standardization to compare players performance across different years. We could also check to see if the predictor variables had the similar correlations to match win percentage across years.
